<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911202-0094</DOCNO><DOCID>911202-0094.</DOCID><HL>   Anglo American Posts   21% Increase in Net   For Fiscal First Half   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/02/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7C</SO><CO>   ANGLY</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>AFRICA (AF)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)</RE><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- Anglo American Corp. ofSouth Africa, the world's largest mining concern, said netincome in its fiscal first half ended Sept. 30 rose 21% to655 million rand ($233.9 million), or 282 cents a share, from540 million rand, or 233 cents a share, in the year-earlierperiod.   Anglo American said the higher earnings were largely dueto investment income, which increased 6% to 630 million rand.</LP><TEXT>   Julian Ogilvie Thompson, Anglo American's chairman, saidexports are likely to increase in 1992 as the remainingeconomic sanctions against South Africa are lifted.   However, Mr. Thompson said he expects trading conditionsin South Africa and abroad to remain depressed for theremainder of the company's fiscal year, which ends March 31,1992.   Despite the profit increase, Anglo American shares fell 25cents to 126.50 rand in trading in Johannesburg.</TEXT></DOC>